Online E-commerce Data Analysis

Abhilash Singh

Jul 29, 2020·15 min read

1. Introduction

More customers mean more business. Intuitively, it is safe to assume that a company’s ability to attract increasing number of customers has a direct relationship to its increasing sales. However, simply increasing the number of customer base can prove to be a vanity metric, meaning that it would not fulfill its ability to drive business. Moreover, acquiring or keeping the right customers can prove to be more effective in increasing the sales along with saving money instead of mindlessly spending resources on lost causes.

With the help of our data, we would try to generate insights aiding in a successful wholesale channel. The dataset which we will be analyzing is for a UK-based online retail store which majorly sells gift products. The customer base of the company are mainly wholesale retailers. These wholesalers are entities buying products in bulk, generally with a low price tag.

To implement a successful wholesale strategy, let us inspect our data and learn what could be a potential plan of action to drive the business.

Following is a quick walkthrough to the whole analysis done in Python. For more information on the codes, please find the project on my GitHub.

2. Data Cleaning

The online retail dataset and its related information can be found here.

df ----> Our DataFrame

The dataset has 8 attributes ranging from Invoice (Invoice Number), StockCode (Product Item Code), Description (Product Name), Quantity (Number of items bought), InvoiceDate (Time of Purchase), Customer ID (Unique Customer Identification), Price (Price in Pounds), and Country (Place of Transaction). Additionally, the dataset is supposedly large with 1033036 instances.

There is a significant portion of transactions having missing customer ids. We can’t completely neglect these transactional fields as they might be important in other purposes. For now, let us keep it as it is.

# Cancelled Orders - Does not count towards the revenue stream.
------------------------------------------------------------cancel_df = df[df['Invoice'].str.contains('C', na = False)]
cancel_df.reset_index(drop=True)

Invoices starting with ‘C’ are cancelled orders. As they do not count towards the revenue stream, we can remove these transactional fields from the data. Similarly, few transactions with Invoice Code starting with ‘A’ are associated to bad debt adjustments.

What Is a Bad Debt Expense?

"A bad debt expense is recognized when a receivable is no longer collectible because a customer is unable to fulfill their obligation to pay an outstanding debt due to bankruptcy or other financial problems. Companies that extend credit to their customers report bad debts as an allowance for doubtful accounts on the balance sheet, which is also known as a provision for credit losses."

Cleaned Dataset

# Removing Unwanted Transactions
------------------------------------trans_df = df[~df['Invoice'].str.contains('C', na = False)]

trans_df.loc[:,'Revenue'] = np.nan

trans_df.loc[:,'Revenue']= trans_df.loc[:,'Quantity']*trans_df.loc[:,'Price']

trans_df.reset_index(drop=True)trans_df = trans_df[~trans_df.Invoice.str.contains('A', na = False)]
trans_df = trans_df[trans_df['Price']!=0]
trans_df.reset_index(drop=True)

Ultimately, after removing the unnecessary fields related to cancelled orders and credit adjustments, we’ve done some basic cleaning prior to our exploration and have obtained a dataset where the transactions are actually adding to the revenue stream. Nonetheless, we might need to clean it frequently as we further delve into the data.

4.1 Classifying Customers

# Classifying Customers as New and Repeat# Based on any determined time period such as Daily, Weekly or Yearly, we can classify them as new or loyal.# Lets classify the customers based on time of purchase.cust_type=uk_df.drop_duplicates(['Invoice','Customer ID'])cust_type.reset_index(drop=True, inplace = True)cust_type.loc[:,'Type']=np.nanfor cust in cust_type['Customer ID'].unique():
    cust_type.loc[cust_type[cust_type['Customer ID']==cust].index,'Type']='Repeat'
    cust_type.loc[cust_type[cust_type['Customer ID']==cust].index[0],'Type']='New'cust_type

In the classification done above based upon the time of purchases, a customer making the very first purchase will be classified as ‘New’ and for every subsequent purchase made after that with a new invoice, the customer will be classified as a ‘Repeat’ purchaser.

4.4 Customer Lifetime Value

Customers tend to be of more value when they stay with the business for a longer period. Customer loyalty is one of the predictors driving the value of customers in businesses. Every business has its own way of calculating lifetime value.

If we can know the cost that goes into acquiring a customer, then the customer lifetime value becomes a more valuable metric in knowing whether we must continue to pursue new customers while still being profitable.

With our current data we will try to calculate the lifetime value with a simple formula.

Customer Lifetime Value (CLV) = Average Order Value(AOS) * Average Order Frequency(AOF) * Average Customer Lifespan(ACL)

i) CLV for Average Customer

a) Average Order Size (AOS)

“The average order size (AOS) is the average amount of money that a customer spends each time they place an order. The average order size is calculated by calculating your total customer revenue for a given period and dividing the total orders performed by these customers to calculate your average order size.”

aos = join.Revenue_x.sum()/len(join['Invoice'].unique())
aosOutput: 429

The bill value per invoice is around 429 pounds.

b) Average Order Frequency (AOF)

“The average order frequency (AOF) represents the average amount of orders placed by each customer. Your average order frequency (AOF) is calculated by compiling the total number of orders for a given period and dividing it by the total number of customers for a given period.”

aof = (len(join['Invoice'].unique()))/(len(join['Customer ID_x'].unique()))print("{:.2f}".format(aof))Output:6.27

The average of a customer making an unique purchase is approximately 6 times. However, for this particular calculation, we are considering both new and repeat puchasers and the average frequency of repeat purchasers is expected to be more than this value.

c) Average Customer Value (ACV)

“The average customer value (ACV) is the average revenue value that each customer brings to your business during a given timeframe. The average customer value can be determined by multiplying the average order size (AOS) with the average order frequency (AOF).”

acv = (aos*aof)/2print("Average Customer Value Per Year is {:.2f} Pounds.".format(acv))Output:Average Customer Value Per Year is 1344.79 Pounds.

As we have two years of data, we divide the average value by 2.

d) Average Customer Lifespan (ACL)

“The average customer lifespan is the average number of days between first order date and last order date of all of your customers.”

total_days = np.sum((cust_type.groupby('Customer ID').InvoiceDate.max() - cust_type.groupby('Customer ID').InvoiceDate.min()).dt.days)Output: total_days = 1475507
total_cust = len(cust_type['Customer ID'].unique())Output: total_cust = 5350
acl = (total_days/total_cust)/365 
print("Average Customer Lifespan Per Year is {:.2f}.".format(acl))Output:
Average Customer Lifespan Per Year is 0.76.

The average duration a customer stays with the business is around 9 months (12*0.76).

e) Customer Lifetime Value (CLV)

“To calculate your average customer lifetime value (CLV) using this simple method, multiply your average customer lifespan (ACL) to your average customer value (ACV).”

clv = acl*acv
print("Average Customer Lifetime Value is {:.2f}.".format(clv))Output:
Average Customer Lifetime Value is 1016.13.

Customer Lifetime Value calculation is different for every business case. In our case, we have used the simplest formula to calculate the average customer lifetime value. In a nutshell, the more purchases the customers makes the more loyal the customer becomes, increasing the customer lifetime value.

a) The average customer lifetime value per year comes to be around 1016 pounds. In this case, the average cost of acquisition or average cost of serving one customer per year needs to be definitely below 1016 pounds, in order to be profitable.

b) In our case, there are many non repeating customers. By simply converting them to make repeat purchases even with average order size can result in a drastic increase of the lifetime value.

c) Similarly, increasing the average order size of these customers can also result in higher clv.

ii) CLV for Loyal Customer

Let’s calculate the simple CLV for repeat purchasers.

The customer lifetime value for repeat customers is drastically higher than the naive clv calculated earlier. This is solely because of their higher average order size and frequency of buying.

This suggests that how our strategy focused on customer retention with higher order volume can be of more value to the business. Coming up with ways to make customers loyal will be the key to success.

5. Baseline Time Series Forecasting

Any type of reliable predictions on how our business can shape out in future can support us in dealing with future problems with decreased irrationality. Time Series is one such forecasting technique, which estimates our variable against time. There are many factors causing business to behave in a particular way. Although it is not practical to know the exact cause of that behaviour, we can still make decent estimation.

Time Series forecasting requires a great deal of factors ranging from assuming explainable predictors to parameter estimation. However, we can make use of simple benchmark models to make forecasts in order to get a baseline estimate, and then try sophisticated forecasting models to beat the baseline predictions.

Let’s try to make some baseline time series predictions for the Year 2012 based on the Total Biweekly Revenue of our past two years transactional data.

The time series seems to follow no rising or falling trend. However, there seems to be a weak seasonality in the revenue generated biweekly.

The store seems to close operations during the final week of the year. The revenue majorly rise during the final quarter of the year. Maybe, as holidays are near, more retailers tend to stockpile products as it might be cheaper for them to buy supplies around this time.

5.1 Benchmark Models

To test the accuracy, we need to compare our predictions with some test observation. In order to do that, we will divide our biweekly revenue data of two years (2010–2011) into train and test observations, with each comprising of 26 instances.

a) Naive Forecast

For naive forecasts, we simply set all forecasts values to be the value of the last observation in our series. In simpler terms, it means drawing a horizontal straight line from the last observation in our train data to the forecasted period.

b) Mean Forecast

In mean forecast, we expect the forecast values to be the average value of the all the previous observations.

c) Drift Forecast

Drift forecasting is where we calculate the average change of increase or decrease across the series and fitting it into the future.

d) Seasonal Naive Forecast

In seasonal naive, we assume that the forecast value will be similar to the value of the observation in the same time during the last season. For example, revenue on January 1st this year would be similar to the revenue on January 1st last year based on our yearly seasonal period.

# Defining Baseline Forecasts Functions.# NAIVE FORECASTdef naive_f(train, test):
    
    # Its basically same as the last value
    
    forecast = test.copy()
    for i in forecast.index:
        forecast[i]=train[-1]
    
    return forecast# MEAN FORECASTdef mean_f(train, test):
    
    # Its basically same as the last value
    
    forecast = test.copy()
    for i in forecast.index:
        forecast[i]=test.mean()
    
    return forecast# DRIFT FORECASTdef drift_m(train, test):
    
    avg_drift = (train[-1] - train[0])/len(train)
    
    forecast = test.copy()
    
    multiplier = (train[-1] + avg_drift)
    
    for i in forecast.index:
        
        forecast[i] = multiplier
        
        multiplier = (forecast[i] + avg_drift)
        
    return forecast# SEASONAL NAIVEdef snaive(data, test, period): # Period - Period of Seasonality (Bi-Weekly)
    
    forecast = data.shift(period)[len(train):]
    return forecast
Accuracy of Baseline Models:

RMSE OF MEAN FORECAST IS 102203.52
RMSE OF NAIVE FORECAST IS 124127.92
RMSE OF DRIFT FORECAST IS 239147.05
RMSE OF SEASONAL NAIVE FORECAST IS 45361.79

Here, we can see that the root mean square error (rmse) value for our seasonal naive method is the lowest among all. Even from the graph, we are able to view that the predictions fit the test data well.

5.2 Walk Forward Validation For Seasonal Naive

As we see in our seasonal naive forecast of biweekly revenue stream (26 observations in an year), the period of seasonality is yearly. Therefore, the seasonal lag was 26 (T-26). What if there was another lag for which the predictions would have been more better i.e. have lower RMSE?

Lets test that.

Based on the plot, we can confirm that at delay none other than 26, our seasonal naive model has the lowest rmse value.

5.3 Residual Analysis (Seasonal Naive)

To test whether the model has accurately fitted our forecasting models and is free of any unexplainable behaviour, there are certain criteria that residuals must meet to ensure the usability of the model. They are as follows:

a) Residuals must have a constant variance and zero mean. If not, then the model tends to be biased.

b) Residuals must have no autocorrelation. If the residuals have significant correlation with its lagged version, then the model seems to be miss out on capturing information while fitting.

c) Residuals must follow a normal distribution.

Based on the residual plots, we can see that the residuals may or may not be constant, as the variation seems to be not so constant.

Secondly, there are no significant autocorrelations among the lagged version of residuals, suggesting that the forecast shows some potential and can be further improved upon.

Lastly, the residuals are negatively skewed when we ignore the positive error on the right and could have followed a normal distribution if there were more random errors.

The number of observations used in our model are less and we must take that into account. If we had more data, the forecast would have been more reliable. Moreover, there are other forecasting techniques that can be used to improve our baseline models in order to get a reliable forecast.

6. Recommendations

Based on our analysis and limitedness of our dataset features, there are certain assumptions that we must keep in mind before acting on actionable recommendations. Mostly, data trends developed are supposed to be verified with complementary tests before decision-making.

Targeting New Customers — The store must look out for new vendors who might be interested in a particular segment of gift products. In a way, competitor analysis can be carried out to find out who their customers are. Additionally, as we analyzed that new customers tend to spend less during their first purchase, first time buyers can be provided with discounts or added benefits such as free delivery, and replacement guarantee.

Building Trust — The longer the customer lifespan is, the more valuable the customer becomes. This is dependent on how effectively the store can build trust with their both sets of customers (New and Repeat). Trust can be developed with services such as faster on-time deliveries, easy returns, or seamless checkouts. Increased customer engagement can also aid in building relationship by predicting their demands and ensuring what they need in particular from the product or service.

Increasing Purchase Frequency — Providing recommendations to the retail customers based on the products they have had most success with and by researching their market demands. Making things easier for them with when and what to buy helps in increasing orders frequently.

Segmenting Lifetime Value — Segmenting the customers based on their lifetime value and analyzing those segments over the span of their relationship with our business can tell us how their behaviour may change across the timeframe. For example, if a high valued customer stops buying or delays their purchasing frequency, predicting the reason of cause can help us in decreasing the churn rate of higher valued customer segments.

Just before changing the process based on data trends, it is always mandatory to confirm the hypothesis or assumptions with the help of other external data, statistical tests, and yes of course, domain knowledge.
